00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:54.080
prone to eating too much
of something unhealthy,

00:46:54.080 --> 00:46:57.176
I don't think having a little
water is going to hurt you.

00:46:57.176 --> 00:46:59.230
I'm OK with that.

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:00.680
Yeah.

00:47:00.680 --> 00:47:03.050
It seems-- I'm on-board.

00:47:03.050 --> 00:47:03.610
Yeah.

00:47:03.610 --> 00:47:05.320
I just don't want
people to focus so much

00:47:05.320 --> 00:47:07.770
on the number on the scale.

00:47:07.770 --> 00:47:08.550
Yeah.

00:47:08.550 --> 00:47:10.509
But that seems like a
reasonable healthy to do.

00:47:10.509 --> 00:47:12.341
AUDIENCE: So what's a
good way to figure out

00:47:12.341 --> 00:47:14.250
your range, like your
healthy weight range?

00:47:14.250 --> 00:47:17.205
Is it just when you start to
plateau using healthy weight

00:47:17.205 --> 00:47:18.345
loss methods or what?

00:47:18.345 --> 00:47:19.220
TRACI MANN: Oh, yeah.

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:20.000
That's a good way to look at.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:21.916
OK, so that's the-- I
get this question a lot.

00:47:21.916 --> 00:47:25.230
And it's, I think, the
hardest question to answer

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:28.550
scientifically because
there's not research on this

00:47:28.550 --> 00:47:31.050
that I've seen about
how to nail in on this.

00:47:31.050 --> 00:47:35.340
So what it seems to me,
what I sort of concluded

00:47:35.340 --> 00:47:37.706
by talking to lots
of people about this,

00:47:37.706 --> 00:47:41.459
is the middle of your
sort of set range

00:47:41.459 --> 00:47:43.000
is going to be the
weight, it's going

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.530
to be the thing you weigh
when you've eaten reasonably,

00:47:47.530 --> 00:47:50.290
without dieting, but
without binge eating.

00:47:50.290 --> 00:47:54.360
So you've eaten, like, a really
kind of basic amount of food.

00:47:54.360 --> 00:47:57.460
And you've not been
totally sedentary.

00:47:57.460 --> 00:47:59.570
But you haven't, like,
just won a race either.

00:47:59.570 --> 00:48:00.570
So you know what I mean?

00:48:00.570 --> 00:48:03.920
So you're really in the
middle of all these behaviors

00:48:03.920 --> 00:48:06.120
that we know we're
supposed to do.

00:48:06.120 --> 00:48:09.370
And that's going to kind of
be the middle of your range.

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:11.100
And another way
people notice this

00:48:11.100 --> 00:48:14.110
is it's the weight that you
keep seeming to come back to.

00:48:14.110 --> 00:48:15.832
You just keep going back there.

00:48:15.832 --> 00:48:18.040
So whatever you do, suddenly
you're back there again.

00:48:18.040 --> 00:48:18.840
Oh, really?

00:48:18.840 --> 00:48:19.620
Am I here again?

00:48:19.620 --> 00:48:21.730
And then you can use
these healthy strategies

00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:24.920
to go 10 pounds
less or whatever,

00:48:24.920 --> 00:48:27.420
depending on how much you
weighed to begin with.

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:27.920
Yeah.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:28.420
Exactly.

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:34.230
But I can't point at like a
scientific, like, calculation

00:48:34.230 --> 00:48:36.510
that you can use to get there.

00:48:36.510 --> 00:48:37.820
That would be cool, though.

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:39.959
But, yeah, that doesn't exist.

00:48:39.959 --> 00:48:41.250
AUDIENCE: So thanks for coming.

00:48:41.250 --> 00:48:45.310
But just to be clear,
my lack of willpower

00:48:45.310 --> 00:48:48.166
is not the primary reason
why my weight fluctuates

00:48:48.166 --> 00:48:50.040
is what you're saying
or my current weight is

00:48:50.040 --> 00:48:50.735
the way it is?

00:48:50.735 --> 00:48:53.460
Is that like-- just so
I can tell my wife that.

00:48:53.460 --> 00:48:55.940
TRACI MANN: It's not-- Right.

00:48:55.940 --> 00:48:56.889
Definitely.

00:48:56.889 --> 00:48:57.430
AUDIENCE: No.

00:48:57.430 --> 00:48:59.510
In all seriousness,
like I remember

00:48:59.510 --> 00:49:01.750
high school I was--
for all of high school,

00:49:01.750 --> 00:49:03.040
I was probably like 160.

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:05.430
And then university hit,
like that the freshman 15,

00:49:05.430 --> 00:49:07.542
I just went to, like, 180--

00:49:07.542 --> 00:49:08.250
TRACI MANN: Yeah.

00:49:08.250 --> 00:49:08.720
You're giant.

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:09.230
AUDIENCE: --and stayed there.

00:49:09.230 --> 00:49:09.730
Yeah.

00:49:09.730 --> 00:49:10.570
I'm a giant, I know.

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:11.020
TRACI MANN: That's a huge
human who's talking now.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:12.530
AUDIENCE: But I stayed
there for the longest time,

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:14.321
even though I tried to
do all these things.

00:49:14.321 --> 00:49:16.740
So how does your
theory explain-- is it

00:49:16.740 --> 00:49:18.500
just my hormones
changed in university.

00:49:18.500 --> 00:49:22.230
Therefore, like, I'm now
stuck at this new plateau,

00:49:22.230 --> 00:49:23.420
kind of thing?

00:49:23.420 --> 00:49:24.836
TRACI MANN: So,
yeah, the research

00:49:24.836 --> 00:49:28.210
has showed that--
you see lots of diets

00:49:28.210 --> 00:49:31.170
out there that say they're the
change your set point diet.

00:49:31.170 --> 00:49:32.415
I've seen this exact thing.

00:49:32.415 --> 00:49:34.040
There's absolutely
no evidence that you

00:49:34.040 --> 00:49:35.720
can lower your set point.

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:38.210
But, unfortunately,
there is some evidence

00:49:38.210 --> 00:49:42.620
that it can creep upward,
does this slowly over time,

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:47.860
with large life changes,
such as going off to college,

00:49:47.860 --> 00:49:50.820
when you change your
eating habits in a big way.

00:49:50.820 --> 00:49:52.900
Lots of people, when
they get married,

00:49:52.900 --> 00:49:55.130
have very big changes
in their eating habits.

00:49:55.130 --> 00:49:58.570
And you see it creeping upward.

00:49:58.570 --> 00:50:01.180
Women, during
menopause, same thing.

00:50:01.180 --> 00:50:03.040
You see this creep upward.

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:04.050
So it can creep.

00:50:04.050 --> 00:50:06.300
AUDIENCE: And then, just to
follow up on her question,

00:50:06.300 --> 00:50:09.890
how long should you do this,
trying of figure out your set

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:12.490
point or set range?

00:50:12.490 --> 00:50:14.550
Like how long you have
to eat healthy and not

00:50:14.550 --> 00:50:15.320
binge eat, and--

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:16.736
TRACI MANN: A
healthy, healthyish.

00:50:16.736 --> 00:50:18.819
AUDIENCE: --diet?

00:50:18.819 --> 00:50:19.860
TRACI MANN: I don't know.

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:23.380
Again, there's not a
clear science to that.

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:28.025
So I'm going to pull a number
out of the sky for you.

00:50:28.025 --> 00:50:28.900
Would you like me to?

00:50:28.900 --> 00:50:30.040
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:50:30.040 --> 00:50:32.480
TRACI MANN: Let's say,
how about a month?

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:34.150
How about a month?

00:50:34.150 --> 00:50:35.455
That sounds about right, right?

00:50:35.455 --> 00:50:38.120
If you do-- yeah,
maybe a couple weeks,

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:40.790
three weeks,
something like that.

00:50:40.790 --> 00:50:42.507
Definitely not a
huge amount of time.

00:50:42.507 --> 00:50:43.340
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:43.340 --> 00:50:44.120
TRACI MANN: Please?

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:45.510
AUDIENCE: Did you
look at the psychology

00:50:45.510 --> 00:50:48.040
of stress and how some people
eat when they're stressed--

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:48.370
TRACI MANN: Yes.

00:50:48.370 --> 00:50:49.340
AUDIENCE: --and
some people can't

00:50:49.340 --> 00:50:50.423
eat when they're stressed?

00:50:50.423 --> 00:50:51.720
TRACI MANN: It's true.

00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:57.110
So emotional eating is a big
issue in the dieting world.

00:50:57.110 --> 00:50:59.720
So there's a couple of
different things about stress.

00:50:59.720 --> 00:51:03.520
One is that I've done research
with my former student, Janet

00:51:03.520 --> 00:51:07.040
Tomiyama, where we found
that dieting itself

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:09.697
causes a physiological
stress response in your body.

00:51:09.697 --> 00:51:11.530
This could be another
reason why diets don't

00:51:11.530 --> 00:51:13.092
lead to long-term weight loss.

00:51:13.092 --> 00:51:17.380
So stress is clearly a problem.

00:51:17.380 --> 00:51:20.190
What it looks like
is that the people

00:51:20.190 --> 00:51:22.750
who eat in response
to stress tend

00:51:22.750 --> 00:51:27.640
to be dieters, people
trying to not eat.

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:29.550
People trying not to
overeat are the ones who

00:51:29.550 --> 00:51:31.020
eat in response to the stress.

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:34.170
Whereas people who aren't
worrying about their eating

00:51:34.170 --> 00:51:36.850
are the ones who eat less
when they're stressed.

00:51:36.850 --> 00:51:43.570
So what it looks like to us is
that stress messes up diets.

00:51:43.570 --> 00:51:47.060
Dieters are more likely to
overeat in response to stress.

00:51:47.060 --> 00:51:48.910
And stress messes things up.

00:51:48.910 --> 00:51:54.910
So removing stress is a good,
important strategy for-- well,

00:51:54.910 --> 00:51:55.840
for overall health.

00:51:55.840 --> 00:51:58.230
I mean stress is
extremely bad for you

00:51:58.230 --> 00:52:00.140
regardless of whether
or not you're dieting.

00:52:00.140 --> 00:52:02.640
So removing stress
is an important part

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:04.530
of being a healthy person.

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:08.030
And it will also help
you not gain weight.

00:52:08.030 --> 00:52:12.690
I'll say one more thing about
emotional eating, if I may,

00:52:12.690 --> 00:52:15.360
which is about
eating comfort food.

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:18.930
This is the strangest thing
we ever found in our research.

00:52:18.930 --> 00:52:22.240
Is that eating comfort food
doesn't do anything special

00:52:22.240 --> 00:52:23.740
for your mood.

00:52:23.740 --> 00:52:25.830
It doesn't do anything
different for your mood

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:28.000
than eating any other food.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.130
And it doesn't do anything
different for your mood

00:52:30.130 --> 00:52:32.410
than not eating food.

00:52:32.410 --> 00:52:35.270
We tested it in all these
different comparisons

00:52:35.270 --> 00:52:36.850
and it didn't matter.

00:52:36.850 --> 00:52:40.470
Everything, even time,
made your mood slowly

00:52:40.470 --> 00:52:44.580
creep upward after we-- first,
we messed up people's moods.

00:52:44.580 --> 00:52:45.933
And then we looked at what--

00:52:45.933 --> 00:52:46.591
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:46.591 --> 00:52:47.840
This is how you have to do it.

00:52:47.840 --> 00:52:50.720
And then we looked at what
happened when we gave them

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:52.150
either their own
personal comfort

00:52:52.150 --> 00:52:54.840
food, or a neutral
food, or a food

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:57.120
that they like just as
much as their comfort food,

00:52:57.120 --> 00:52:58.160
or no food at all.

00:52:58.160 --> 00:53:00.820
And in every case,
their mood improved.

00:53:00.820 --> 00:53:03.250
But the comfort food didn't
make it improve more.

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:05.790
So because of this
I've come to believe

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:08.450
that comfort food is
the thing that you

00:53:08.450 --> 00:53:10.510
crave when you're feeling bad.

00:53:10.510 --> 00:53:13.320
It's the thing you want
when you're feeling bad.

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:16.410
But it doesn't actually do
anything special for you.

00:53:16.410 --> 00:53:19.090
And maybe you think it does
because when you eat it,

00:53:19.090 --> 00:53:20.069
you feel better.

00:53:20.069 --> 00:53:22.360
But you don't realize, you
don't have the control group

00:53:22.360 --> 00:53:24.450
in your head, which is
if you hadn't eaten it,

00:53:24.450 --> 00:53:26.866
you'd have felt better too or
if you eaten something else,

00:53:26.866 --> 00:53:28.340
you'd have felt better too.

00:53:28.340 --> 00:53:32.570
So we encourage people to not
reach for their comfort food

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:34.392
when they're feeling
bad, thinking

00:53:34.392 --> 00:53:35.850
that it's going to
make them better

00:53:35.850 --> 00:53:37.370
in some special, extra way.

00:53:37.370 --> 00:53:39.360
It's not.

00:53:39.360 --> 00:53:40.980
I would say save
the comfort food,

00:53:40.980 --> 00:53:42.980
save that particular food,
for when you're happy

00:53:42.980 --> 00:53:45.620
and can really enjoy
and appreciate it.

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:50.630
But you don't really need an
excuse to eat those foods.

00:53:50.630 --> 00:53:52.430
You can eat them when you wish.

00:53:52.430 --> 00:53:53.890
Just don't justify
them, thinking

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:56.785
it's going to make you feel
better because no, it's not.

00:53:56.785 --> 00:53:58.660
I mean it's not going
to make you feel worse.

00:53:58.660 --> 00:53:59.950
Don't go there.

00:53:59.950 --> 00:54:01.969
It's not going to do that.

